# Module 02: Network Architecture
### 🏗️ Hierarchical Layers & Network Design

Hierarchical design is the cornerstone of a secure and scalable network. By organizing the network into distinct layers, we implement **Layers of Control**, ensuring that a failure or breach in one segment does not compromise the entire infrastructure.

---

## 🏢 Physical Hierarchy: The 3-Tier Model
For medium to large-scale environments, a structured physical topology is essential to maintain a high security posture while ensuring scalability.

### 1. Access Layer
*   **Role:** The entry point where end-devices (Laptops, IoT, Smartphones) connect.
*   **Security Focus:** This is the first line of defense. Technologies like **NAC (Network Access Control)** and **Port Security** are implemented here to prevent unauthorized physical access.

### 2. Distribution Layer
*   **Role:** The "Policy Layer" that bridges Access and Core.
*   **Security Focus:** This layer manages **VLAN routing**, **Access Control Lists (ACLs)**, and security policies. It acts as a boundary to contain broadcast traffic and security threats.

### 3. Core Layer
*   **Role:** The high-speed backbone of the network.
*   **Security Focus:** Minimal processing happens here to maintain maximum speed. Its primary security contribution is **Redundancy (Fault Tolerance)**, ensuring the network stays up even if a primary switch fails.

> **Note on 2-Tier (Collapsed Core):** In smaller environments, Core and Distribution functions are merged. While cost-effective, it offers less isolation than a full 3-Tier design.

---

## 🛡️ Tiered Application Security: Access vs. Data
The core security principle of hierarchical layering is the logical and physical **separation of user access from sensitive data.**

### 2-Tier vs. 3-Tier Application Design


| Feature | 2-Tier Architecture (Risk) | 3-Tier Architecture (Defense) |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Structure** | Web/App Tier -> Database | Web Tier -> Application Tier -> Data Tier |
| **Data Access** | Web-app has direct query access to DB. | Web-app only talks to the App Tier. |
| **Breach Impact** | Attacker can dump entire user tables. | Attacker only gets a "yes/no" logic response. |
| **Security Logic** | Combined presentation & business logic. | **App Tier acts as a Whitelist**, enforcing Least Privilege. |

**The DMZ (Demilitarized Zone):** High-risk assets (Web Servers) are placed in the DMZ "fence," while high-impact assets (Databases) are stored behind it in the internal network. This physical separation slows down attackers and prevents direct access to data stores.

